name":"Dolman","meanings":["English: topographic name denoting a ‘dweller by the boundary mark’ (compare   Dole  ).","English: nickname for a ‘dull, foolish man’. Compare   Doll   5.","Dutch: topographic name from <i>dol</i> ‘swampy land’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’, or a nickname from the adjective <i>dol</i> ‘wild, fierce, rash, foolish’ for such a man."]},{"name":"Daul","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Dieter, Florian, Kurt, Liselotte, Wilhelm.","German:","nickname, perhaps for a tall thin person, from Middle Low German <i>dūle</i> ‘reed, cattail’. It is also found in France (Alsace). Compare   Dole   3."]},{"name":"Doles","meanings":["English: altered form of   Dole  , with excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Slovenian: probably from a shortened form of <i>hudoles</i> (literary ‘evil wood’), a term denoting a wayfaring tree (Viburnum lantana) and an alder buckthorn (Rhamnus frangula)."]}]},{"name":"Esther","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by a Jewish captive who became the wife of the Persian king Ahasuerus. Her Hebrew name was <i>Hadassah</i> ‘myrtle’, and the form <i>Esther</i> is said to be a Persian translation of this, although others derive it from Persian <i>stara</i> ‘star’. It may also be a Hebrew form of the name of the Persian goddess <i>Ishtar</i>. According to the book of the Bible that bears her name, Esther managed, by her perception and persuasion, to save large numbers of the Jews from the evil machinations of the royal counsellor Haman.  See also  Hester ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Esther Dole was born in 1368, in Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with John William Hammond I. She died in 1419, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1368–1419":"1368–1419","1366–1440":"1366–1440","1419–1450":"1419–1450","1368":"1368","1366":"1366","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1419":"1419","Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Suffolk, Inglis